Question One - Three

  1. Choose any product category of your choice. Download Twitter data for all the leading brands in that product category.

  2. Generate Document-Term-Frequency matrices (either TDF, DTF, TFIDF) after pre-processing data for stop word removal, special character removal, number removal, and case conversion.

  3. Generate Wordclouds for each of the Brands separately. Do they reveal anything? Summarize insights.

InstallAndLoadPackages<-function(x) {
  x <- as.character(x)
  if (!require(x,character.only=TRUE))
    {
      install.packages(pkgs=x,repos="http://cran.r-project.org") 
      require(x,character.only=TRUE)
   } 
}
PrepareTwitter<-function() { 
  InstallAndLoadPackages("bitops")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("RCurl")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("RJSONIO")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("ROAuth")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("SnowballC")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("modeest")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("tm")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("rJava")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("RWeka")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("RWekajars")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("stopwords")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("twitteR")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("wordcloud")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("tidytext")
  InstallAndLoadPackages("topicmodels")
}

TweetFrame<-function(searchTerm,n,SINCE) {
  # This function TweetFrame() - Return a dataframe based on a search of Twitter
  tweetList <- searchTwitter(searchTerm,n,since=SINCE,lang='en')
  # as.data.frame() coerces each list element into a row
  # lapply() applies this to all of the elements in twtList 
  # rbind() takes all of the rows and puts them together
  # do.call() gives rbind() all rows as individual elements
  tweetDF<- do.call("rbind", lapply(tweetList,as.data.frame))
  # This last step sorts the tweets in arrival order
  return(tweetDF[order(as.integer(tweetDF$created)), ]) 
}

This likely reflects either an uptick in positive or negative reviews associated with the new model.

Question Four: Topic Modeling With LDA

Perform Topic modeling via Latent Dirchlet Allocation (LDA) on the DTF matrix. Extract top 10 topics. Interpret the topics. Are they Brand specific?

system.time(cell.topicmodel <- topicmodels::LDA(t(TDM_cell), 10, method = "Gibbs", control = list(iter=2000, seed = 0622)))
##    user  system elapsed 
##   2.306   0.014   2.342
cell.topics <- topicmodels::topics(cell.topicmodel, 1)
## In this case I am returning the top 30 terms.
cell.terms <- as.data.frame(topicmodels::terms(cell.topicmodel, 30), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
##Viewing the topics
cell.terms[1:10]

From the top ten topics above, we can see that they are not brand specific as “porschegt” and “rover” are included in the same topic. Rather, the topics are a collection of words from the tweets that maximize the posterior probability of observing the combined twitter data corpus. As such, each word listed under the topic contributes a certain weight to its topic and in aggregate these ten topics are assumed to explain the entire space (i.e., our Twitter corpus) and would not be brand specific.

From the above, we can see the contribution of each word to the model’s explanation of the entire Twitter corpus. Unlike LDA which segments out its explanation of the corpus into topics and the corresponding word composition (i.e., multiple topics per tweet), above we can directly see the contribution of each word, by cluster (based on highest association).

from the cluster contributions above we can see that they do not represent a single brand and rather represent a combination of words that in aggregate form the cluster. From the one cluster we can see that the top words are “landrover”, “tow”, and “ability” which leads me to conclude that this is a potential segments of Twitter users that value the tactical abilities of the car brands. From another cluster we can see that this is a segment of Twitter users likely tweeting about their new purchase as the words “finally”, “got”, and “yet” are among the top ten words. We can also see that this cluster of Twitter users also tweets about family and friends along with their cars. From the last cluster, some of the top words are “landrover”, “defender”, “supercharged”, and “powerful” which suggest that this cluster of Twitter users focuses on the power of the cars when tweeting.

Question Six: Brand Map

Can you generate a Brand Map from your analysis? Can you generate a list of Delighters/Disappointers for leading Brands in the category? If not – state the limitations of the analysis.

No - With the Twitter data available we are limited to only the tweets from people who are extremely excited or disappointed. The average consumer who is reasonably satisfied with a product does not tweet or provide feedback to the brand, a case of response bias.

In order to create an accurate brand map we would need thousands of consumer perceptions to uncover the determinant attributes.

While we are unable to create an accurate brand map, we are able to classify the twitter responses as a list of delighters and disappointers, because as mentioned, the consumers who tweet about products are either overly satisfied or disappointed with the product.

Question Seven: What are the sampling limitations of this approach?

The limitations to using twitter data are: biased responses (extreme satisfaction or displeasure), not representative of entire population as consumers who tweet are likely younger, have easy access to the internet and Twitter accounts, like voicing their opinions, and due to the nature of tweets the data is a consolidated thought and not necessarily a logical perception of a brand or product.

Question Eight: Brand Health

Should this approach be relied upon to produce Product Positioning maps (Brand Maps)? Will the resulting Brand Map represent the “true” Brand Health?

As mentioned in question six, no. While you theoretically could create a brand map, it would not be reliable as the data is biased and would not represent the brand’s “true” health as many consumers who are either marginally satisfied or disappointed or not on Twitter are not included in the sample, as such it is not representative of a true brand population.

Question Nine: Should this approach be relied upon to produce Brand Delighters and Disappointers for Brands?

Yes, while Twitter data is not indicative of all of a brand’s consumers, it does represent the segment that either feels extremely positive or negative about the brand. A such, Twitter data can be useful in order to provide insight as to the extremely positive and negative determinant attributes.

Question Ten: Will the results be reliable?

For assessing potential extremely positive and negative determinant attributes, Twitter data is still not the most reliable source. Mainly, this is due to the fact that many people tweet just to complain or give false praise, as such even for the extreme responses the data is still susceptible to bias.
